231 – Power of Two
Problem Statement

Given an integer n, return true if it is a power of two. Otherwise, return false.

A number is a power of two if it can be represented as:

n=2
x

where x >= 0.

Examples
Input: n = 1
Output: true
Explanation: 2^0 = 1

Input: n = 16
Output: true
Explanation: 2^4 = 16

Input: n = 3
Output: false
Approach: Check Powers of 2 Iteratively

The idea is to generate powers of 2 from 2^0 to 2^30 and compare each value with n.

Since the maximum positive integer in Java (int) is less than 2^31, checking up to 2^30 is sufficient.

Algorithm
Iterate from i = 0 to 30.
Compute 2^i using Math.pow(2, i).
If the generated value equals n, return true.
If no match is found after the loop, return false.
Code
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 31; i++) {
            if (n == Math.pow(2, i)) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
n = 16
Execution
i	2^i	Match with 16?
0	1	No
1	2	No
2	4	No
3	8	No
4	16	Yes

Return true.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(31) ≈ O(1)

The loop runs at most 31 times.

Space Complexity
O(1)

No extra space is used.

Key Insight
Powers of two within the integer range are limited (2^0 to 2^30).
By generating and comparing these values, we can determine whether n is a power of two.
Although this solution works, a bit manipulation approach is more efficient and is commonly preferred in interviews.
Optimized Bit Manipulation Solution
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        return n > 0 && (n & (n - 1)) == 0;
    }
}

Why it works?

A power of two has exactly one set bit in its binary representation.
n & (n - 1) removes the rightmost set bit.
If the result becomes 0, the number had only one set bit, meaning it is a power of two.
Optimized Complexity
Time Complexity: O(1)
Space Complexity: O(1)

